00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:11.630
ANN MEI CHANG:
It's so fun for me

00:00:11.630 --> 00:00:13.920
to be here for a
number of reasons.

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:16.820
One is I live two blocks away,
so this is the easiest speaking

00:00:16.820 --> 00:00:18.082
gig possible.

00:00:18.082 --> 00:00:19.790
The other, as I was
telling, Jacquelline,

00:00:19.790 --> 00:00:20.780
it's like coming
back to high school.

00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:22.484
I left Google about
eight years ago,

00:00:22.484 --> 00:00:24.650
and it's like all these
memories come flooding back.

00:00:24.650 --> 00:00:27.330
This building actually wasn't
a Google building when I left.

00:00:27.330 --> 00:00:30.720
But it's consistent
branding and all that,

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:33.470
so it brings back
lots of good memories.

00:00:33.470 --> 00:00:36.320
So when I left Google
eight years ago,

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:39.652
I decided to spend the second
half of my career working

00:00:39.652 --> 00:00:41.360
towards social good,
specifically focused

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:42.680
on Google poverty.

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:45.470
And I had spent my whole
career in the tech world.

00:00:45.470 --> 00:00:47.060
I studied as a
software engineer,

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:49.100
as an engineering director.

00:00:49.100 --> 00:00:52.040
I knew how to build
software, but I knew nothing

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:53.040
about global poverty.

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:55.410
So I knew I had a lot to learn.

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:58.130
And I wasn't really sure
how I could contribute.

00:00:58.130 --> 00:01:00.470
At first, everyone
was trying to come

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:03.290
to me to help them build
an app for this or that

00:01:03.290 --> 00:01:05.510
or build a website, and
it wasn't clear to me

00:01:05.510 --> 00:01:08.400
that that was really going
to be a highest and best use.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:09.600
So I set out to learn.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:12.320
And one of the things
that really struck me,

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:14.930
as I dug into these
issues, was that there's

00:01:14.930 --> 00:01:18.900
these immense, complex
challenges out there.

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:23.450
And there's incredible people
working on these issues,

00:01:23.450 --> 00:01:26.600
with such dedication, a lot
of resources going into it.

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:30.410
But it just felt like we
were barely making a dent.

00:01:30.410 --> 00:01:33.590
And so I think my journey
over the last eight years

00:01:33.590 --> 00:01:35.360
has really been
trying to figure out

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:39.170
not how I can make my own tiny
little mark on some corner

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:41.150
of some issue, but really
looking at the system

00:01:41.150 --> 00:01:45.076
and saying, how can we do this
better and trying to bring some

00:01:45.076 --> 00:01:46.700
the experiences that
I've had at Google

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:51.440
and other places to some of
these big social challenges.

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:53.540
And so I'm assuming
people here generally

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:55.130
have heard of the
"Lean Startup."

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:57.140
Is that, yes?

00:01:57.140 --> 00:01:59.570
And so I think the
"Lean Startup" just

00:01:59.570 --> 00:02:01.580
is one of the books that's
really captured some

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:03.210
of the best practices
of innovation

00:02:03.210 --> 00:02:05.600
I think we live and
breathe here at Google.

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:07.790
And Eric talks about
the "Lean Startup"

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:10.940
as a methodology for building
products and services

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:12.680
under conditions of
extreme uncertainty,

00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:14.180
which is true for
startup companies,

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:15.320
is true for a lot
of things we're

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:16.850
trying to invent
here at Google that

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:18.750
have never been done before.

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:22.010
And I would argue it's
equally if not more true

00:02:22.010 --> 00:02:23.870
when it comes to
social challenges.

00:02:23.870 --> 00:02:28.130
Because we're talking about big,
complex, long-term entrenched

00:02:28.130 --> 00:02:31.910
issues that we don't
have solutions for.

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:37.580
And so in that case, there's
a huge amount of uncertainty,

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:38.790
but yet what seems--

00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:41.240
what I found to be
true is that most

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:42.770
of the organizations
out there who

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:44.840
are trying to tackle
these challenges

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:48.110
are really good at
predictable execution.

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:51.350
They like to create
these grandmaster plans.

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:53.660
Maybe they don't like
to do it, but the system

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:55.460
of applying for
grants and so forth,

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:57.560
forces them to create
these grandmasters plans,

00:02:57.560 --> 00:03:01.370
and they're expected to
execute rigidly to that plan--

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:06.630
sort of the opposite of what we
all know innovation looks like.

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:08.840
So when there is
such uncertainty,

00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:10.610
I think what we
need to do instead

00:03:10.610 --> 00:03:12.440
is look at approaches
that help accelerate

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:13.820
the speed of learning.

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:18.610
And this probably seems
obvious to all of you.

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:20.839
And I know lots of
nonprofit leaders

00:03:20.839 --> 00:03:22.880
who have picked up the
"Lean Startup," have heard

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:25.430
about other innovation tools,
such as human-centered design,

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:27.210
and they say, this
makes a lot of sense.

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:28.310
We want to do this.

00:03:28.310 --> 00:03:30.530
And then, they get stuck
because they struggle

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:34.070
with a number of barriers,
such as the nature of how

00:03:34.070 --> 00:03:39.110
restrictive funding can be, the
difficulty of measuring impact,

00:03:39.110 --> 00:03:42.620
and the length of time it
can take to realize impact,

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:45.200
and also the whole notion
of experimentation,

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:48.440
running A/B tests sounds great
when you're building a website.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:50.180
It's a little harder
when you're talking

00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:52.370
about experimenting on
really vulnerable people who

00:03:52.370 --> 00:03:53.900
are living on the edge.

00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:55.970
And so that's really
why I wrote this book.

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:58.090
It's not to invent
something new.

00:03:58.090 --> 00:03:59.840
I don't come up
with new methodology

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:01.160
here that didn't exist before--

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:03.650
but to really look at how
these best practices that

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:05.930
have come out of
places like Google

00:04:05.930 --> 00:04:09.890
can be adapted for the
realities of the context

00:04:09.890 --> 00:04:12.200
that organizations
work in who are trying

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:15.950
to deliver social good
until, in the process

00:04:15.950 --> 00:04:17.990
of writing the
book, I spoke with--

00:04:17.990 --> 00:04:20.930
I was lucky to interview
over 200 organizations--

00:04:20.930 --> 00:04:23.870
big and small, domestic and
international, nonprofits

00:04:23.870 --> 00:04:26.210
and for-profits, funders
and implementers,

00:04:26.210 --> 00:04:30.540
and really try to see,
among the most successful,

00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:33.440
what were the core
elements of their success?

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:36.890
And I kind of boiled it
down into three principles.

00:04:36.890 --> 00:04:41.780
And what was surprising to me
is that the traditional way

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:45.170
of going about doing social good
is the exact opposite of this.

00:04:45.170 --> 00:04:48.710
We tend to think too
small, start too big,

00:04:48.710 --> 00:04:52.070
and get diverted by many
things on the path to impact.

00:04:52.070 --> 00:04:53.720
So let me start
with "think big."

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:56.750
So what I found is
that most nonprofits,

00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:59.300
the way that they
go about their work

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:01.970
is that they plan
based on constraints.

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:03.150
We have this much money.

00:05:03.150 --> 00:05:04.579
We have this many people.

00:05:04.579 --> 00:05:05.870
We have this grant opportunity.

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:07.410
There's this size and scope.

00:05:07.410 --> 00:05:10.985
And so what can we do
within this box we're in?

00:05:10.985 --> 00:05:13.600
And they usually do some good.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:15.714
But it rarely moves the needle.

00:05:15.714 --> 00:05:17.880
This is where it feels like
we're doing so much work

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:20.171
and working so hard, and yet
we're never getting ahead.

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:26.140
I think the first shift
that needs to happen

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:29.170
is that we need to stop
planning based on constraints

00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:31.529
and start planning
based on the need.

00:05:31.529 --> 00:05:33.070
What is the actual
need in the world?

00:05:33.070 --> 00:05:38.470
What would actually move the
needle on changing, addressing

00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:40.000
a real problem?

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:41.690
And that's a really
different approach.

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:42.790
You know, here in
Silicon Valley,

00:05:42.790 --> 00:05:45.400
we know everybody's-- all the
startup companies are running

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:48.460
around with their PowerPoint
decks that show the hockey

00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:51.190
stick curve of how they're
going to reach a billion people.

00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:54.610
That doesn't happen
in the social sector

00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:56.560
very often, at
least, and it needs

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:58.600
to because the problems
are just as big.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:01.510
Let me just illustrate
what that looks like.

00:06:01.510 --> 00:06:04.810
Over the last 30 years, we've
made slow but steady progress

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:07.960
on core social
challenges like access

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:10.540
to clean water,
electricity, and sanitation.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:16.690
This is really hard,
painstaking work because we're

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:18.400
trying to reach people
who are very poor,

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:22.360
who are living in very remote
areas, and so it's slow.

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:24.280
And yet during this
same period of time,

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:27.100
adoption of mobile
phones skyrocketed.

00:06:27.100 --> 00:06:29.467
And what's the difference here?

00:06:29.467 --> 00:06:32.050
One of the differences is that
this is something people really

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:32.815
want in demand.

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:37.930
I've heard so many
stories of people

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:42.124
who will top up their mobile
phone before they'll buy food.

00:06:42.124 --> 00:06:44.290
And so today, there's more
people with mobile phones

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:46.640
than have a toilet.

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:50.050
The other side is, on the
supply side, the companies that

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:51.960
manufacture mobile
phones make a profit,

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:54.340
can plow that into making
better phones for cheaper

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:55.510
and distributing them.

00:06:55.510 --> 00:06:57.220
The telecom companies
that sell minutes

00:06:57.220 --> 00:06:59.761
are able to make a profit, and
so they can build more towers,

00:06:59.761 --> 00:07:03.230
reach more rural areas,
deliver service more cheaply.

00:07:03.230 --> 00:07:05.650
And so through this
combination of strong demand

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:09.100
and strong supply, you
see this kind of growth.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:11.416
And certainly, not everything
in the social sector

00:07:11.416 --> 00:07:12.790
is going to look
like this, but I

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:14.248
think we should
challenge ourselves

00:07:14.248 --> 00:07:17.800
to say, how do we shoot
for something that

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:19.610
has this kind of trajectory?

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:23.320
And I think it's possible
in more cases than we think.

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:27.620
And that starts out by setting
a goal, setting higher sights.

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:29.860
A nonprofit here in
the Bay Area called

00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:33.250
"Earn" is focused on helping
low-income Americans develop

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:34.690
a habit of savings.

00:07:34.690 --> 00:07:36.970
And after 10 years
in business, they

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:39.430
were being lauded at being
the top of their field,

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:42.310
having 7,000 micro
savings accounts.

00:07:42.310 --> 00:07:46.130
And the founder, Ben Mangan,
one day woke up and he thought,

00:07:46.130 --> 00:07:47.920
we're getting all
this recognition,

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:51.580
but, really, there are an
estimated 50 to 70 million

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:53.650
Americans who could
benefit from this.

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:55.810
And we're reaching
7,000 after 10 years.

00:07:55.810 --> 00:07:57.980
We're barely
scratching the surface.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:07:59.920
And so he got up
at an awards dinner

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:02.080
and made this grand
announcement that they

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:05.370
were going to reach a million
people in the next five years.

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:07.660
That's a big stretch from 7,000.

00:08:07.660 --> 00:08:10.450
But what it did is it forced
Earn to re-look at their model.

00:08:10.450 --> 00:08:14.650
They were doing in-person
visits to each of their clients.

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:16.392
They were doing a
financial match.

00:08:16.392 --> 00:08:18.100
And these things were
feasible if they're

00:08:18.100 --> 00:08:19.806
going to get to the
scope of the need.

00:08:19.806 --> 00:08:22.180
And so it forced them to take
a different look at things.

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:23.860
And they ended up
building a technology

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:26.151
platform that could reach a
lot more people, a lot more

00:08:26.151 --> 00:08:26.950
cheaply.

00:08:26.950 --> 00:08:29.320
And the first year after
rolling out that platform,

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:31.060
they reached 85,000 people--

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:33.789
so more than 10 times as many
as in their first 10 years

00:08:33.789 --> 00:08:34.690
combined.

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:36.309
There's just a
illustration of what

00:08:36.309 --> 00:08:39.704
it can look like to shift your
mindset and to shoot bigger.

00:08:39.704 --> 00:08:41.620
And that often means
that we don't necessarily

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:42.850
know the path there yet.

00:08:42.850 --> 00:08:44.740
But at least if
we're successful,

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:46.180
we can really move the needle.

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:52.870
So the second principle of
Lean Impact is to start small.

00:08:52.870 --> 00:08:57.284
We all know here that, when we
have some great product idea,

00:08:57.284 --> 00:08:58.450
that we want to start small.

00:08:58.450 --> 00:09:01.330
We dog-food things;
we run A/B tests.

00:09:01.330 --> 00:09:05.960
But this is uncommon
in the social sector.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:07.630
And we all know that
by starting small,

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:09.790
we can make a bigger
impact over time,

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:12.100
because we can learn much
more faster, iterate much

00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:16.090
more quickly when we're
experimented with just 5,

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:17.890
or 10, or 100
people versus trying

00:09:17.890 --> 00:09:20.260
to carry the infrastructure
and all the logistics

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:23.140
related to serving
thousands of people.

00:09:23.140 --> 00:09:26.890
So the core of "Lean Startup,"
Eric talks about the Build,

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:28.885
Measure, Learn feedback loop.

00:09:28.885 --> 00:09:31.945
And this is the cycle of
iteration where we build an--

00:09:31.945 --> 00:09:34.720
you know we have a potential
solution, a hypothesis

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:35.980
about what it will do.

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:38.320
We build an experiment,
measure, gather the data,

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:40.070
and we learn and we
iterate through this.

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:43.810
So this is all very familiar
to us in the tech world.

00:09:43.810 --> 00:09:46.330
It's sort of familiar
in the social sector.

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:48.340
The only problem is,
in the social sector,

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:51.290
this cycle usually takes years.

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:53.320
So in the global
development space,

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:57.760
you're often designing a program
for one, or two, or three

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:00.760
years before it
even hits the field.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:02.140
And say it's a
five-year program,

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:04.030
you run it for 2 and 1/2 years.

00:10:04.030 --> 00:10:07.480
You then do your midline
evaluation, which usually

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:09.090
takes a year in and of itself.

00:10:09.090 --> 00:10:10.440
then, you're 3 and 1/2
years into your program,

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:12.020
you get some data,
and then you might

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:14.550
plow what you learned
into your next proposal.

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:17.540
So the whole cycle could
take like five or seven years

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:18.600
to get through.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:22.280
And so if you imagine these
great, complex challenges

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:24.629
and you're only learning on
the cycle of seven years,

00:10:24.629 --> 00:10:26.420
you're not going to
make a lot of progress.

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:28.767
And the world is only
moving faster and faster.

00:10:28.767 --> 00:10:30.350
So the key here is,
how do we speed up

00:10:30.350 --> 00:10:33.500
this feedback loop
for social good so

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:35.540
that we can make
faster progress,

00:10:35.540 --> 00:10:38.150
and can take more risks, and
try more different things,

00:10:38.150 --> 00:10:41.220
can find much better solutions?

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:44.229
And so when it comes
to social impact,

00:10:44.229 --> 00:10:45.770
there's three
dimensions that I think

00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:48.425
we need to test hypotheses
around-- value, impact,

00:10:48.425 --> 00:10:49.130
and growth.

00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:52.070
In the "Lean Startup,"
Eric talks about the value

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:54.200
hypothesis and the
growth hypothesis

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:58.520
is a two-core hypothesis to
test that we do within the tech

00:10:58.520 --> 00:10:59.366
industry, certainly.

00:10:59.366 --> 00:11:00.740
The value hypothesis
is certainly

00:11:00.740 --> 00:11:02.484
not only do people
want your product,

00:11:02.484 --> 00:11:04.150
but they'll demand
it, come back for it,

00:11:04.150 --> 00:11:05.750
tell their friends about it.

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:08.210
Growth is, what is
the engine for growth

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:09.787
that's going to drive adoption?

00:11:09.787 --> 00:11:11.120
Are people going to refer folks?

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:13.070
Are they going to pay money
for it that you can plow back

00:11:13.070 --> 00:11:13.880
into investment?

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.150
And so forth.

00:11:15.150 --> 00:11:17.720
But then for social
impact, we need

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:20.270
to add a third hypothesis,
which is the impact hypothesis.

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:23.210
It's not enough to have
something that people want

00:11:23.210 --> 00:11:25.320
and have it be able
to get to people,

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:27.950
then you can just be talking
about Nike shoes, maybe.

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:29.750
But it also has to
have social impact.

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:33.090
And too often we don't ask the
simple question, does it work?

00:11:33.090 --> 00:11:38.570
Does it deliver the social
benefit that we are seeking.

00:11:38.570 --> 00:11:40.430
And so let me just
talk briefly--

00:11:40.430 --> 00:11:42.410
give a brief example
for each of these three

00:11:42.410 --> 00:11:44.493
and what it might look
like in the social context.

00:11:44.493 --> 00:11:48.290
So for value, this is testing--

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:50.720
is this something that people
will really demand, and use,

00:11:50.720 --> 00:11:52.370
and engage with?

00:11:52.370 --> 00:11:55.200
And a MVP for value
will look very different

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:57.200
and can look very different
in the social sector

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:59.790
than when you're testing
an online service.

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:02.960
In this case, it's a social
enterprise called Copia Global.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:04.460
It's in Kenya.

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:06.800
They set out to look
at how to provide

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:09.050
a much wider range
of consumer goods

00:12:09.050 --> 00:12:12.410
to people living in rural areas
that typically only have access

00:12:12.410 --> 00:12:14.960
to the basic consumer staples.

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:17.720
And so rather than building
out the infrastructure

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:20.480
to transport goods, to
build an online catalog

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:22.430
or ordering system,
and warehouses,

00:12:22.430 --> 00:12:25.630
and all this kind of stuff,
they decided to run an MVP.

00:12:25.630 --> 00:12:28.910
Their MVP consisted
of the CEO Crispin,

00:12:28.910 --> 00:12:31.940
going to the local Walmart
equivalent, the Nakumatt,

00:12:31.940 --> 00:12:34.220
and taking pictures of a
bunch of different products

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:37.670
off the shelves of what he
thought people might like.

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:40.550
And he pasted these into
a handful of catalogs,

00:12:40.550 --> 00:12:42.620
distributed them
to a few villages,

00:12:42.620 --> 00:12:44.760
and stepped back to
see what would happen.

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:46.940
And his questions were,
would people even want

00:12:46.940 --> 00:12:49.100
to order from a catalog?

00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:51.380
What kinds of things
would they order?

00:12:51.380 --> 00:12:54.050
Would agents sell
from the catalog?

00:12:54.050 --> 00:12:56.867
And they learned a lot of
things, just from this process.

00:12:56.867 --> 00:12:58.700
First, they learned
that people would order.

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:00.410
Orders started coming in.

00:13:00.410 --> 00:13:02.690
And when an order would
come in, Crispin himself

00:13:02.690 --> 00:13:05.270
would go run to the store, buy
the product off the shelves,

00:13:05.270 --> 00:13:07.310
and hand carry it
to the village.

00:13:07.310 --> 00:13:09.555
Now this is certainly not
something that could scale,

00:13:09.555 --> 00:13:11.180
but it's something
that he could get up

00:13:11.180 --> 00:13:13.305
and running within a few days.

00:13:13.305 --> 00:13:14.930
And so he validated
the fact that, yes,

00:13:14.930 --> 00:13:17.400
people wanted to order
from the catalog.

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:19.216
This was a value to people.

00:13:19.216 --> 00:13:20.840
He also found out
what kind of products

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:22.490
people wanted to order.

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:25.550
One of the surprises
was that, today,

00:13:25.550 --> 00:13:28.984
one of their most popular
products is cement.

00:13:28.984 --> 00:13:30.650
Not something they
thought of initially,

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:32.729
but if you think
about it, going--

00:13:32.729 --> 00:13:35.270
If you don't have a car going
and getting cement and carrying

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:36.664
it home is actually
kind of hard.

00:13:36.664 --> 00:13:38.330
And so it's something
that people really

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:40.790
value getting delivery of.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:42.830
And then, they had another
surprise, which is,

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:46.010
they originally thought that
the agents that they would use

00:13:46.010 --> 00:13:48.350
would be the people who are
running these kind of kiosk,

00:13:48.350 --> 00:13:50.900
the corner stores
in these villages,

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:53.280
because they were
already selling goods.

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:55.907
But it turned out that
these kiosk owners

00:13:55.907 --> 00:13:58.490
were more interested in moving
the inventory they were already

00:13:58.490 --> 00:14:00.041
carrying in their shops.

00:14:00.041 --> 00:14:01.790
And so they didn't
really try to encourage

00:14:01.790 --> 00:14:03.590
people to buy from the catalog.

00:14:03.590 --> 00:14:06.470
And the people who ended up
making much better agents

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:09.440
were complementary
businesses, like hair salons,

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:11.570
where people would be
waiting to get their haircut,

00:14:11.570 --> 00:14:13.070
they could flip
through the catalog,

00:14:13.070 --> 00:14:15.100
and it would be an
additional stream of income.

00:14:15.100 --> 00:14:16.924
So through this
kind of MVP, again,

00:14:16.924 --> 00:14:18.590
that looks very
different than if you're

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:20.090
testing an online
service, they were

00:14:20.090 --> 00:14:22.790
able to learn a ton of stuff
very quickly very cheaply that

00:14:22.790 --> 00:14:27.080
really helped them
refine their service.

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:29.420
On the impact front, one
of the biggest challenges

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:32.510
is, as I mentioned earlier,
that it can take a long time

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:35.100
to fully realize impact.

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:37.970
One of the examples of where
that's true is in education.

00:14:37.970 --> 00:14:41.160
The educational attainment
can take years to realize.

00:14:41.160 --> 00:14:44.690
Summit Public Schools is another
nonprofit in the Bay Area.

00:14:44.690 --> 00:14:49.490
And they set out with this
idea of Diane Tavenner, who's

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:52.730
the founder, set
out with the idea

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:55.490
that she wanted to run the
school for a diverse student

00:14:55.490 --> 00:14:59.570
body, where 100% of the
students would graduate college.

00:14:59.570 --> 00:15:02.665
Now they brought in all the best
practices that they could find,

00:15:02.665 --> 00:15:05.570
set up a charter school,
and eight years later,

00:15:05.570 --> 00:15:07.100
when their first
cohort graduated

00:15:07.100 --> 00:15:08.510
from college, what
they found was

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:11.190
they were doing significantly
better than average.

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:13.100
And they were getting
all sorts of pressure

00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:14.180
to scale their model.

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:16.650
And Diane said, wait, slow down.

00:15:16.650 --> 00:15:18.860
We're doing really
good, but we're still

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:22.550
far short of the 100% target.

00:15:22.550 --> 00:15:24.200
We can do better.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:26.120
But she also said,
there is no way

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:28.820
I'm waiting another eight years
to try something different

00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:30.270
and see if it works.

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:31.820
And so what she
decided instead is

00:15:31.820 --> 00:15:34.040
to figure out how
to build a culture

00:15:34.040 --> 00:15:35.720
and process for
speeding up learning

00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:37.300
within their organization.

00:15:37.300 --> 00:15:40.730
And that consisted of coming
up with a platform where

00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:41.900
they could capture data.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:44.720
So they moved to a
weekly cycle where

00:15:44.720 --> 00:15:46.400
they would do
student assessments

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:47.630
to see what students learned.

00:15:47.630 --> 00:15:48.950
They would have
focus groups, see

00:15:48.950 --> 00:15:50.741
what people were engaged
with, get feedback

00:15:50.741 --> 00:15:53.270
from teachers, and so forth--
and gather all this data

00:15:53.270 --> 00:15:54.740
on a weekly basis.

00:15:54.740 --> 00:15:58.460
And they ended up running
57 weeks of experiments,

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:00.680
kind of varying the
length, and duration,

00:16:00.680 --> 00:16:02.990
and nature of different
classroom elements,

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:05.600
to come up with this
revolutionary model

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:07.880
of personalized learning.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:10.340
And today, that model
of personalized learning

00:16:10.340 --> 00:16:13.390
has been adopted by
over 300 public schools.

00:16:13.390 --> 00:16:19.160
And last year, their students
had a 99% admission rate

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:20.180
to college.

00:16:20.180 --> 00:16:22.310
So they haven't graduated
yet, but they're

00:16:22.310 --> 00:16:24.200
learning much, much faster now.

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:26.310
And so it's just an example
that, a lot of times,

00:16:26.310 --> 00:16:28.810
even though the full impact may
take a long time to realize,

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:30.500
there's earlier
indicators that we

00:16:30.500 --> 00:16:35.480
can capture that help us improve
and refine our interventions.

00:16:35.480 --> 00:16:41.060
The third pillar of social
innovation is growth.

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:43.340
And I want to share the
example of VisionSpring

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:45.590
to illustrate what
growth might look like,

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:48.530
because it's very different
than in the private sector.

00:16:48.530 --> 00:16:51.320
So VisionSpring set out with--

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:55.700
their audacious goal was
to take an invention that's

00:16:55.700 --> 00:17:00.320
700 years old, that has been
proven to increase productivity

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:03.440
and learning potential,
and that's eyeglasses.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:06.349
We often think of innovation as
got to be some whiz bang latest

00:17:06.349 --> 00:17:09.650
technology, but they took
something that's 700 years old,

00:17:09.650 --> 00:17:14.210
and yet two and a half billion
people who need eyeglasses

00:17:14.210 --> 00:17:16.250
don't have them today.

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:18.210
And so they set out to
try to figure this out.

00:17:18.210 --> 00:17:21.980
They started out by going to
two geographies, El Salvador

00:17:21.980 --> 00:17:23.690
and India, hiring
some people they

00:17:23.690 --> 00:17:26.910
called "vision entrepreneurs"
to do outreach to these--

00:17:26.910 --> 00:17:29.240
to people in rural areas
and provide vision care.

00:17:29.240 --> 00:17:31.130
And they came back
with compelling stories

00:17:31.130 --> 00:17:34.400
of kids who were able
to learn, of adults

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:35.797
who were able to work again.

00:17:35.797 --> 00:17:38.130
And for most nonprofits, they
would be thrilled by this.

00:17:38.130 --> 00:17:41.140
They're making a huge difference
in these people's lives.

00:17:41.140 --> 00:17:43.100
But VisionSpring thought
it wasn't enough.

00:17:43.100 --> 00:17:45.350
They were losing money with
every person they reached.

00:17:45.350 --> 00:17:47.720
They would never be
able to get to scale.

00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:48.440
So they pivoted.

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:51.560
Their second incarnation,
they created vision centers

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:55.970
in more urban areas, and served
a more affluent population,

00:17:55.970 --> 00:17:58.339
and took the profits from
that to cross-subsidize,

00:17:58.339 --> 00:17:59.630
outreach some more rural areas.

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:02.213
And so through this, they became
financially self sustainable.

00:18:02.213 --> 00:18:03.950
Again, the holy grail
for nonprofits--

00:18:03.950 --> 00:18:05.750
I'm making a big
difference, and I'm

00:18:05.750 --> 00:18:07.610
financially self-sustainable.

00:18:07.610 --> 00:18:08.990
But it still wasn't enough.

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:10.970
Because it would have
taken them decades to be

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:13.700
able to scale their
infrastructure to reach

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:15.320
everyone they wanted to reach.

00:18:15.320 --> 00:18:16.400
So they pivoted again.

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:21.380
They ended up partnering with
an organization in Bangladesh

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:24.260
called BRAC that has a network
of community health care

00:18:24.260 --> 00:18:26.480
workers in every
corner of the country

00:18:26.480 --> 00:18:29.404
and provided vision services
through this existing network.

00:18:29.404 --> 00:18:31.070
And so through this
partnership, they've

00:18:31.070 --> 00:18:33.030
now been able to reach
over a million people.

00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:34.530
And through additional
partnerships,

00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:36.870
they've reached over four
and a half million people.

00:18:36.870 --> 00:18:39.470
And so now, they're making
a difference, financially

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:41.390
self-sustainable, and
reaching millions.

00:18:41.390 --> 00:18:43.280
There's only one problem.

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:46.100
Four and a half million
people is a tiny fraction

00:18:46.100 --> 00:18:48.360
of 2 and 1/2 billion people.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:49.919
And they recognized
that this is not

00:18:49.919 --> 00:18:51.710
something any one
organization could solve.

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:53.990
There's a systems problem
that manufacturers

00:18:53.990 --> 00:18:56.360
weren't incentivized to
create low cost enough classes

00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:58.285
and get them distributed
to rural areas.

00:18:58.285 --> 00:19:00.410
Governments weren't taking
care of the basic vision

00:19:00.410 --> 00:19:01.891
needs of their populations.

00:19:01.891 --> 00:19:03.890
And so they started a
public private partnership

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:05.840
called the EYElliance
that brings together

00:19:05.840 --> 00:19:07.550
eyeglass manufacturers,
and governments,

00:19:07.550 --> 00:19:10.370
and nonprofits to look
at these systems issues.

00:19:10.370 --> 00:19:13.850
And one of their first
successes was an MOU

00:19:13.850 --> 00:19:16.280
they signed with the
government of Liberia,

00:19:16.280 --> 00:19:18.650
where the government
agreed to integrate vision

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:21.350
care into their public health
system and public school

00:19:21.350 --> 00:19:22.071
system.

00:19:22.071 --> 00:19:23.570
And so you can
imagine that, as they

00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:25.430
look at this more
on a systemic level,

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:28.610
and try to influence policy
and influence market dynamics,

00:19:28.610 --> 00:19:30.470
that they have a hope
of eventually getting

00:19:30.470 --> 00:19:34.200
to that two and a
half billion number.

00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:37.250
So the last principle
of "Lean Impact"

00:19:37.250 --> 00:19:39.470
is to relentlessly seek impact.

00:19:39.470 --> 00:19:42.050
Now this may seem like
the obvious thing to do.

00:19:42.050 --> 00:19:44.210
After all, these are
mission-driven organizations.

00:19:44.210 --> 00:19:46.100
Of course they're
going to seek impact.

00:19:46.100 --> 00:19:48.650
But it turns out that
there's so many things that

00:19:48.650 --> 00:19:50.660
push in the opposite direction.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:52.970
You've all probably heard
of this phrase, fall in love

00:19:52.970 --> 00:19:54.950
with the problem,
not the solution.

00:19:54.950 --> 00:19:57.440
And what I see with a
lot of organizations

00:19:57.440 --> 00:20:00.200
is that people get
excited about applying

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:03.740
a particular technology
or the particular role

00:20:03.740 --> 00:20:05.540
of their organization,
or they have

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:08.300
pride of ownership over the
design of an intervention

00:20:08.300 --> 00:20:11.580
that they have invested
their time and energy into

00:20:11.580 --> 00:20:13.720
and have seen make a difference.

00:20:13.720 --> 00:20:15.330
One of the indicators
of this, to me,

00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:19.890
as I talk to lots of different
international NGOs who work

00:20:19.890 --> 00:20:22.650
in education, or health
care, or agriculture--

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:24.750
and a lot of them have
similar programs--

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:28.010
and every one of them will tell
me their program is the best.

00:20:28.010 --> 00:20:30.870
And they can't all
possibly be right.

00:20:30.870 --> 00:20:32.850
And so we're not
really being rigorous

00:20:32.850 --> 00:20:37.420
in looking at what really is
the best solution to a problem.

00:20:37.420 --> 00:20:40.140
People are just getting
accustomed to promoting

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:40.920
their thing--

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:42.170
because it's on their website.

00:20:42.170 --> 00:20:43.920
It's what they
pitched to funders.

00:20:43.920 --> 00:20:46.800
Everybody's saying why
their thing is the best.

00:20:46.800 --> 00:20:49.050
And very few of them
can tell me basic--

00:20:49.050 --> 00:20:50.790
answer basic
questions like, what

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:52.920
is the cost effectiveness
of your solution

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:55.090
so that we can actually
compare these things.

00:20:55.090 --> 00:20:57.300
And so part of what
I think we need to do

00:20:57.300 --> 00:21:00.750
is start looking at
the right metrics.

00:21:00.750 --> 00:21:02.446
Eric talks about
the vanity metrics

00:21:02.446 --> 00:21:05.070
as these absolute numbers of the
number of people we've reached

00:21:05.070 --> 00:21:06.720
or the number of
dollars we've raised.

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:08.345
These are the things
that organizations

00:21:08.345 --> 00:21:09.510
tend to highlight if you--

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:11.680
as much as they talk about
mission on the outside,

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:13.710
on the inside, if you go to
the executive team meetings,

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:15.360
this is what they're
talking about--

00:21:15.360 --> 00:21:17.818
how many people did you reach,
how many dollars you raised,

00:21:17.818 --> 00:21:18.930
what's our grant pipeline.

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:22.190
None of these things have
any correlation with impact.

00:21:22.190 --> 00:21:23.940
You can reach a lot
of people, but did you

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:27.130
actually improve their lives?

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:28.860
And even if you did
improve their lives,

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:32.740
could somebody else have done
more with the same resources?

00:21:32.740 --> 00:21:35.850
So instead, what I think
we need to focus on

00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:39.360
is the metrics on the
right, which are, what

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:40.840
I call the innovation metrics.

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:43.860
These are the unit-level metrics
on value, growth, and impact--

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:46.980
things such as the adoption
rate, the unit costs,

00:21:46.980 --> 00:21:50.880
the success rate, that will
pay dividends over time

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:52.656
as you optimize those.

00:21:52.656 --> 00:21:54.030
And a lot of times,
we don't even

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:57.750
know what this data is when it
comes to social interventions.

00:21:57.750 --> 00:21:59.910
We're focusing too much
on actually just reaching

00:21:59.910 --> 00:22:01.980
more and more people
and not on really

00:22:01.980 --> 00:22:08.020
optimizing for the basic
unit drivers of success.

00:22:08.020 --> 00:22:10.710
So I'll just wrap up
by saying, the one--

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:13.050
I could sum down one
thing that I really

00:22:13.050 --> 00:22:15.150
wanted to accomplish
with this book is

00:22:15.150 --> 00:22:17.700
to change the minds of
the world for anybody,

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:20.790
any organization who
cares about social good,

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:23.460
whether you're
volunteering your time,

00:22:23.460 --> 00:22:24.990
you're donating
your money, you're

00:22:24.990 --> 00:22:28.140
working on a project
for social good

00:22:28.140 --> 00:22:32.010
or otherwise, I think we
need to raise the bar.

00:22:32.010 --> 00:22:36.030
Companies are expected to
maximize shareholder value,

00:22:36.030 --> 00:22:36.935
maximize profits.

00:22:36.935 --> 00:22:38.310
And we have all
these regulations

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:41.880
that force them to do so, and
companies will relentlessly

00:22:41.880 --> 00:22:43.770
maximize their profits.

00:22:43.770 --> 00:22:47.070
I think we need to bring that
same attitude to social good.

00:22:47.070 --> 00:22:48.930
If you're a mission-driven
organization,

00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:52.950
or you claim to be, it's not
enough to deliver some good.

00:22:52.950 --> 00:22:54.960
We too easily let
ourselves settle

00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:56.220
for delivering some good.

00:22:56.220 --> 00:22:57.690
We made some difference.

00:22:57.690 --> 00:22:59.640
Instead, I think we
need to hold ourselves

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:04.180
accountable to maximizing the
impact and scale of our work.

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:08.910
And so, to me, that means
setting those audacious goals,

00:23:08.910 --> 00:23:11.370
really thinking about
the size and the need,

00:23:11.370 --> 00:23:13.740
but then starting
small, and testing,

00:23:13.740 --> 00:23:17.490
and optimizing what we deliver
around value growth and impact

00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:20.670
and staying relentlessly
focused on achieving

00:23:20.670 --> 00:23:22.720
the maximum impact possible.

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:23.424
Thank you.

00:23:23.424 --> 00:23:28.867
