00:25:40.620 --> 00:25:44.910
that we can help do the most
good as Google, Google.org,

00:25:44.910 --> 00:25:47.850
and we're really leaning into
providing resources, but most

00:25:47.850 --> 00:25:49.050
importantly our Googlers.

00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:52.240
And so we're sending out
teams for six months at a time

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:52.740
to really--

00:25:52.740 --> 00:25:53.400
ANN MEI CHANG: Oh, that's great.

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:54.380
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
--yeah, deeply embed.

00:25:54.380 --> 00:25:56.720
And we've got some folks
here who've done that.

00:25:56.720 --> 00:26:00.060
But you know, you raise a good
point, too, in the book about,

00:26:00.060 --> 00:26:04.740
I think sometimes we can have
some hubris in the tech world

00:26:04.740 --> 00:26:08.250
and think that we sort of know
everything and can just go in

00:26:08.250 --> 00:26:09.161
and solve everything.

00:26:09.161 --> 00:26:11.160
And you know, those folks
in the nonprofit world

00:26:11.160 --> 00:26:13.290
are just not that bright
or not that ambitious.

00:26:13.290 --> 00:26:15.850
And I'm going to go
in and teach them.

00:26:15.850 --> 00:26:17.640
So what do you
think is something

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:20.790
that you've picked up from
being on both sides of the table

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:23.504
that tech can learn from
the nonprofit sector?

00:26:23.504 --> 00:26:25.670
ANN MEI CHANG: Well, there's
sort of the macro thing

00:26:25.670 --> 00:26:26.711
and then the micro thing.

00:26:26.711 --> 00:26:29.070
On the macro level, you
talked about the value growth

00:26:29.070 --> 00:26:30.620
and impact hypotheses.

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:32.700
And Eric started out
with Silicon Valley

00:26:32.700 --> 00:26:35.440
being value and growth
over the two hypotheses.

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:38.260
I think that we're seeing
pressure now around the world

00:26:38.260 --> 00:26:40.510
on the impact that tech has.

00:26:40.510 --> 00:26:44.160
And I think that my hope is
not only does the social sector

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:47.130
adopt some of these tools
from the tech sector,

00:26:47.130 --> 00:26:48.930
but maybe some of
this will flow back,

00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:51.990
where we can also be looking
at the impact hypothesis

00:26:51.990 --> 00:26:55.300
as something we should
equally weigh and value

00:26:55.300 --> 00:26:56.430
as we develop products.

00:26:56.430 --> 00:27:00.420
Because the kind of reach that
Google and other companies

00:27:00.420 --> 00:27:03.840
have is huge, and we need
to think about the impact

00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:05.310
we're having.

00:27:05.310 --> 00:27:09.600
At a micro level, I think that
one of the things I've seen

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:12.690
is tech people coming into
the social sector, especially

00:27:12.690 --> 00:27:15.090
global development, which is
hard because you're working

00:27:15.090 --> 00:27:17.100
with people who are very,
very different than you,

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:19.225
who are very far away, who
have different cultures,

00:27:19.225 --> 00:27:21.270
and languages, and lives.

00:27:21.270 --> 00:27:23.950
And I think there can
be this hubris to say,

00:27:23.950 --> 00:27:27.120
hey, we can build
you an app for that,

00:27:27.120 --> 00:27:29.190
not to mention they don't
have smartphones or let

00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:31.650
alone a signal, right?

00:27:31.650 --> 00:27:35.565
And so people who have
been in the social sector

00:27:35.565 --> 00:27:37.830
and global development
for a long time

00:27:37.830 --> 00:27:40.920
have worked in and out
with the local populations

00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:44.100
and have a much better
understanding of the realities

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:45.770
of what people live with.

00:27:45.770 --> 00:27:49.290
And I think we
can often be naive

00:27:49.290 --> 00:27:51.912
and just assuming that
if we build an app

00:27:51.912 --> 00:27:53.370
or provide the
technology that it's

00:27:53.370 --> 00:27:54.494
going to change everything.

00:27:54.494 --> 00:27:57.960
And there's so many-- you know,
that's like 2% of the problem.

00:27:57.960 --> 00:28:00.240
There are so many
other dynamics at play.

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:01.320
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Well,
you talked, too, in the book,

00:28:01.320 --> 00:28:03.660
and Bryan Stevenson has this
phrase, "get proximate--"

00:28:03.660 --> 00:28:05.460
you know, how
important it is for us

00:28:05.460 --> 00:28:08.160
to just roll up our
sleeves, and go, and listen,

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:10.500
listen with empathy.

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:12.940
How has that played
out in your career?

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:15.630
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah, I think
it's so essential to get

00:28:15.630 --> 00:28:17.182
proximate, and not just, like--

00:28:17.182 --> 00:28:19.140
I think sometimes people
think, "get proximate"

00:28:19.140 --> 00:28:21.480
means go take a trip
to Kenya for a week,

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:23.160
and talk to some
people, and come home,

00:28:23.160 --> 00:28:25.267
and then you build your product.

00:28:25.267 --> 00:28:26.850
One of the examples
I give in the book

00:28:26.850 --> 00:28:29.150
is of Proximity Designs--

00:28:29.150 --> 00:28:30.640
incorporated that
into their name.

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:32.390
When they decided to
work with smallholder

00:28:32.390 --> 00:28:34.430
farmers and Myanmar,
they literally picked up

00:28:34.430 --> 00:28:35.470
and moved there.

00:28:35.470 --> 00:28:36.920
Because what it
allowed them to do

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:40.310
is, every day, be living among
and talking to the farmers they

00:28:40.310 --> 00:28:42.710
were trying to serve
and be able to design

00:28:42.710 --> 00:28:46.460
with them in the whole
process and every day

00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:49.190
be able to bring prototypes
and get their feedback.

00:28:49.190 --> 00:28:51.590
And so they were able to
speed up their feedback loop

00:28:51.590 --> 00:28:53.870
by being there and getting
that kind of feedback.

00:28:53.870 --> 00:28:55.550
And I think that's
just so essential.

00:28:55.550 --> 00:28:58.312
Because we make so
many bad assumptions,

00:28:58.312 --> 00:29:00.020
especially when we're
working with people

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:01.228
who are so different than us.

00:29:04.674 --> 00:29:06.590
One of the things I
learned is that innovating

00:29:06.590 --> 00:29:09.289
is so much harder in the social
sector for a number of reasons.

00:29:09.289 --> 00:29:10.580
But this is one of the reasons.

00:29:10.580 --> 00:29:12.020
Like, here, when we
build products at Google,

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:13.394
we're generally
building products

00:29:13.394 --> 00:29:15.510
that are for people like us.

00:29:15.510 --> 00:29:16.760
And during my time at Google--

00:29:16.760 --> 00:29:17.160
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
Which is part of problem.

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:18.618
ANN MEI CHANG:
Yeah, during my time

00:29:18.618 --> 00:29:21.230
at Google, the products
that we failed at the most

00:29:21.230 --> 00:29:24.110
were ones for people who
were not quite like us.

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:26.090
Because we were so used
to-- we have a system--

00:29:26.090 --> 00:29:27.240
JACQUELLINE FULLER: And
because we're not very diverse,

00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:28.730
there's a lot of people
that aren't quite like us.

00:29:28.730 --> 00:29:29.990
ANN MEI CHANG: Yes, exactly.

00:29:29.990 --> 00:29:31.531
Yeah, I think that's
really an issue.

00:29:31.531 --> 00:29:33.670
But when you're building
products for people like,

00:29:33.670 --> 00:29:34.670
you can use the product.

00:29:34.670 --> 00:29:35.711
You dog-food the product.

00:29:35.711 --> 00:29:37.365
You get generally
pretty good feedback.

00:29:37.365 --> 00:29:38.990
And you have a pretty
good sense of how

00:29:38.990 --> 00:29:40.157
people are going to respond.

00:29:40.157 --> 00:29:41.781
That's completely
different when you're

00:29:41.781 --> 00:29:43.320
working with
vulnerable populations,

00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:44.736
whether domestic
or international,

00:29:44.736 --> 00:29:49.310
that just don't have the same
instincts, assumptions, culture

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:49.880
that we do.

00:29:49.880 --> 00:29:50.964
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Mm-hm.

00:29:50.964 --> 00:29:52.463
So one more question,
then I'm going

00:29:52.463 --> 00:29:53.800
to open it up to the audience.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:58.070
So you talked about the
importance of nonprofits

00:29:58.070 --> 00:29:59.960
being able to be
self-sustaining,

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:02.960
and I think some of the problem
in the nonprofit culture,

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:06.770
frankly, or a lot of it, is
derived to just how skewed they

00:30:06.770 --> 00:30:10.960
are by funders, and that
funders acted more responsibly

00:30:10.960 --> 00:30:14.030
and in line with providing
incentives around true impact.

00:30:14.030 --> 00:30:18.110
I loved your slide about
measuring true impact.

00:30:18.110 --> 00:30:22.220
But do you have a thought
on this social businesses,

00:30:22.220 --> 00:30:24.570
versus nonprofits,
versus governments?

00:30:24.570 --> 00:30:27.920
You know, how do you think
about the different roles

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:30.350
that each of those kinds
of groups can play in this?

00:30:30.350 --> 00:30:31.891
ANN MEI CHANG: It's
a great question.

00:30:31.891 --> 00:30:35.820
And funders is probably the
biggest barrier to innovation

00:30:35.820 --> 00:30:39.510
that I consistently hear
when I talk to nonprofits.

00:30:39.510 --> 00:30:43.260
And it's because of the
nature of restrictive funding.

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:47.360
I think that both funders
and nonprofits, or donors

00:30:47.360 --> 00:30:50.750
and nonprofits, are
trying too much to solve

00:30:50.750 --> 00:30:52.380
the problem themselves.

00:30:52.380 --> 00:30:54.500
And if you look at just
the numbers in terms

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:56.630
of how much donor
dollars there are

00:30:56.630 --> 00:30:59.120
and how much reach
nonprofits have,

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:01.700
they're not set up
for almost any problem

00:31:01.700 --> 00:31:04.350
to be able to deliver at
the scale that's needed.

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:07.910
And so what I think we need to
do is shift our thinking a bit

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:09.860
and think of donors
and nonprofits

00:31:09.860 --> 00:31:13.010
more as incubators, as
the startups if you will,

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:14.600
to figure out the
better solutions.

00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:16.460
Because they can be
close to the problem.

00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:19.430
They can experiment, and
take risks, and figure out

00:31:19.430 --> 00:31:21.950
how to deliver better services.

00:31:21.950 --> 00:31:26.450
And when they do,
then, I think there's

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:29.759
like three general paths
to scale that are possible.

00:31:29.759 --> 00:31:31.800
And it depends on the type
of thing you're doing.

00:31:31.800 --> 00:31:34.550
But one path of scale is if you
can develop a private sector

00:31:34.550 --> 00:31:35.390
business model.

00:31:35.390 --> 00:31:38.000
But that may start with a
nonprofit or social enterprise

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.720
because the upside
may not be big enough

00:31:41.720 --> 00:31:44.570
and the risk may be too high
for a private sector company

00:31:44.570 --> 00:31:45.660
to take it on.

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:48.260
And so this is where donors and
nonprofits can sort of de-risk

00:31:48.260 --> 00:31:50.630
and refine a model, and
then be able to hand it

00:31:50.630 --> 00:31:54.240
off to private sector to
be a to take it forward.

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:57.680
The other end of the extreme
is for basic social services.

00:31:57.680 --> 00:31:59.480
Government is really
the path to scale.

00:31:59.480 --> 00:32:02.060
Government spends
a lot of money,

00:32:02.060 --> 00:32:04.730
many more times than
philanthropy spends,

00:32:04.730 --> 00:32:07.289
providing social services
for its citizens,

00:32:07.289 --> 00:32:08.830
whether it's education
or health care

00:32:08.830 --> 00:32:10.670
are some of the biggest areas--

00:32:10.670 --> 00:32:13.010
but so where we
can help government

00:32:13.010 --> 00:32:16.640
more cost effectively spend
its money by coming up

00:32:16.640 --> 00:32:19.670
with new and better
solutions, we

00:32:19.670 --> 00:32:21.860
can leverage that money
that government is already

00:32:21.860 --> 00:32:24.590
spending in a much better way
to make a bigger difference.

00:32:24.590 --> 00:32:27.350
And the third kind of
path is some variation

00:32:27.350 --> 00:32:32.300
on replication or franchising,
that maybe it's not just

00:32:32.300 --> 00:32:34.430
one private sector
company or one government,

00:32:34.430 --> 00:32:37.010
but it can be lots of
smaller organizations

00:32:37.010 --> 00:32:40.520
in different places
who are all adapting--

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:43.070
microfinance is sort of a great
example of the replication

00:32:43.070 --> 00:32:44.640
model, getting to
millions of people,

00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:48.167
people in both the private
sector and nonprofit models.

00:32:48.167 --> 00:32:49.250
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Great.

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:51.250
Well, let's open it up
to questions in the room.

00:32:51.250 --> 00:32:53.170
And do we have any on
the Livestream as well?

00:32:53.170 --> 00:32:55.080
Yeah, go ahead.

