and latrines not really.

00:33:19.434 --> 00:33:22.100
And I think there's a reason why
Google cell phones and we don't

00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:24.050
sell latrines.

00:33:24.050 --> 00:33:26.510
I guess my question is, what
do you think happens in, say,

00:33:26.510 --> 00:33:28.920
a decade when social
impact organizations all

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:31.830
start to stay that it becomes
this culture of, like, desire

00:33:31.830 --> 00:33:33.700
to scale and kind of
a demand, and need,

00:33:33.700 --> 00:33:37.150
and baseline as to scale,
and then, they start to say,

00:33:37.150 --> 00:33:39.330
OK, we're going to ignore
the hard-to-scale problems

00:33:39.330 --> 00:33:42.072
and only address the
ones that's scalable?

00:33:42.072 --> 00:33:43.530
Is that something
you think there's

00:33:43.530 --> 00:33:44.875
a way to hedge against that?

00:33:44.875 --> 00:33:46.840
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah,
it's a great question.

00:33:46.840 --> 00:33:50.170
So I do think that, in
just about every case,

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:52.290
we should be aiming
for scale, but I

00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:54.790
don't think that means we should
pick off the easy problems.

00:33:54.790 --> 00:33:57.090
I think that social sector
organizations should

00:33:57.090 --> 00:33:59.535
focus on the toughest problems.

00:33:59.535 --> 00:34:01.160
The reason that we
need a social sector

00:34:01.160 --> 00:34:03.724
is where both markets and
governments are failing.

00:34:03.724 --> 00:34:05.265
And so if markets
and the governments

00:34:05.265 --> 00:34:06.660
are already working,
like mobile phones,

00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:08.550
you don't need nonprofits
to get involved.

00:34:08.550 --> 00:34:10.260
So they, generally,
should be focused

00:34:10.260 --> 00:34:13.570
on the problems that aren't
being taken up by others.

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:16.800
And I think for any
kind of problem,

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:18.290
we should think
about how to scale.

00:34:18.290 --> 00:34:20.600
I get a lot of questions
from folks about,

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:22.476
how about local
community organizations.

00:34:22.476 --> 00:34:23.850
And one of the
things I would say

00:34:23.850 --> 00:34:26.406
is that, yes, local
community organizations

00:34:26.406 --> 00:34:28.739
are essential-- to be close
to the community, understand

00:34:28.739 --> 00:34:30.550
the community, and so forth.

00:34:30.550 --> 00:34:33.060
But I would ask a few questions.

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:38.070
First, are you delivering
the most cost-effective

00:34:38.070 --> 00:34:39.360
intervention that you could?

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:42.030
Whether it's you're trying
to help the homeless,

00:34:42.030 --> 00:34:43.750
or feed the hungry,
or whatever--

00:34:43.750 --> 00:34:46.350
are you doing this as cost
effectively as possible?

00:34:46.350 --> 00:34:49.380
If not, can you learn
from or take practices

00:34:49.380 --> 00:34:51.659
from other organizations
that are figuring this out.

00:34:51.659 --> 00:34:54.810
And if you are, if you've gotten
to the most cost-effective way

00:34:54.810 --> 00:34:57.270
to do this and you're also
reaching all the people that

00:34:57.270 --> 00:34:59.455
need this, you should
absolutely tell other people

00:34:59.455 --> 00:35:01.830
how you're doing this so they
don't have to all figure it

00:35:01.830 --> 00:35:02.640
out themselves.

00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:05.470
And scaling doesn't mean having
to scale your organization.

00:35:05.470 --> 00:35:08.530
It means scaling the impact.

00:35:08.530 --> 00:35:10.080
And so I think
there's very few cases

00:35:10.080 --> 00:35:12.480
I can think of where you
wouldn't want to get the scale,

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:13.230
but that doesn't mean--

00:35:13.230 --> 00:35:14.670
I don't see organizations
say, oh, we're

00:35:14.670 --> 00:35:16.530
only going to tackle
problems that get to scale.

00:35:16.530 --> 00:35:19.050
I think they really have the
problems they want to tackle.

00:35:19.050 --> 00:35:23.760
The problem is that they're
really focusing their success

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:25.616
on delivering to a
finite number of people

00:35:25.616 --> 00:35:27.240
instead of looking
at how to really get

00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:29.087
to everyone that needs it.

00:35:29.087 --> 00:35:31.170
AUDIENCE: And my question
is about more tactically

00:35:31.170 --> 00:35:33.360
around when you
think you are ready.

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:35.560
And I think, for context,
like 10 years ago,

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:39.240
if I finish master in
CS, and I got two offers,

00:35:39.240 --> 00:35:41.880
one was in a nonprofit
doing consulting and doing

00:35:41.880 --> 00:35:43.470
capacity-building
for nonprofits.

00:35:43.470 --> 00:35:45.990
And the other one was for
Google being a developer.

00:35:45.990 --> 00:35:47.880
And I wanted to
go to a nonprofit,

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:51.090
but my mentors that said, hey,
good intentions aren't enough.

00:35:51.090 --> 00:35:53.610
Go get your skills,
money, network and stuff.

00:35:53.610 --> 00:35:58.050
So 10 years have gone by, and
I'm still evaluating that.

00:35:58.050 --> 00:36:01.080
And my question is
along the lines of,

00:36:01.080 --> 00:36:03.570
when do you know you're
ready to make a transition?

00:36:03.570 --> 00:36:06.930
And specifically, looking
back, were there muscles

00:36:06.930 --> 00:36:08.670
that you felt you
underflexed and muscles

00:36:08.670 --> 00:36:11.730
that you felt you
over-flexed now

00:36:11.730 --> 00:36:13.022
that you are on the other side?

00:36:13.022 --> 00:36:14.855
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
That's a great question.

00:36:14.855 --> 00:36:16.620
ANN MEI CHANG: It
is a great question.

00:36:16.620 --> 00:36:19.507
I made a somewhat arbitrary
decision in my mid 20s;

00:36:19.507 --> 00:36:21.090
I was going to spend
half of my career

00:36:21.090 --> 00:36:23.226
in tech Silicon Valley
and half of my career--

00:36:23.226 --> 00:36:24.600
so for me, it was
just, like, oh,

00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:27.210
now, I'm 42 or
something like that.

00:36:27.210 --> 00:36:29.255
It's time to do it.

00:36:29.255 --> 00:36:30.630
I don't think
there's one answer.

00:36:30.630 --> 00:36:32.247
I'll tell you my
experience of this.

00:36:32.247 --> 00:36:34.080
Because I think it's
different-- some people

00:36:34.080 --> 00:36:36.780
start from the beginning in
the social sector and do great.

00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:38.730
And other people
come in very late.

00:36:38.730 --> 00:36:42.090
For me, what worked
out well about doing it

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:45.060
mid-career is I
think the reality is

00:36:45.060 --> 00:36:48.450
that you can
personally learn faster

00:36:48.450 --> 00:36:50.790
in the private sector
than social sector.

00:36:50.790 --> 00:36:52.190
There's a lot more resources.

00:36:52.190 --> 00:36:54.839
There's a lot more
talent than expertise.

00:36:54.839 --> 00:36:56.130
There's a lot more competition.

00:36:56.130 --> 00:36:57.480
Things move faster.

00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:00.540
And so I felt like
I developed skills

00:37:00.540 --> 00:37:04.254
at two or three times the rate
I would have by being in Silicon

00:37:04.254 --> 00:37:05.670
Valley then I would
have if I just

00:37:05.670 --> 00:37:07.810
started in the social sector.

00:37:07.810 --> 00:37:10.380
And so the other
thing is I think

00:37:10.380 --> 00:37:12.840
that because there's
a lot of dysfunction

00:37:12.840 --> 00:37:15.420
in the sector, a
lot of us, I think,

00:37:15.420 --> 00:37:18.280
would be pretty frustrated
going into the social sector

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:20.640
in a junior level role,
where we're essentially

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:22.320
executing on those
grand master plans

00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:23.800
that someone came up with.

00:37:23.800 --> 00:37:26.640
And so, for me, it was
more interesting going in,

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:28.770
where I could be in
a senior enough role

00:37:28.770 --> 00:37:32.250
that I had some say over
the planning of things

00:37:32.250 --> 00:37:34.770
and the strategy for things
so that I felt like I

00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:36.240
could make a bigger difference.

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:37.950
And exactly what point
in time there is,

00:37:37.950 --> 00:37:39.825
I don't think there's
an exact science to it,

00:37:39.825 --> 00:37:43.140
but I think that spending enough
time in the private sector

00:37:43.140 --> 00:37:45.250
to build up your skills--

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:47.790
think about what you want your
unique advantage to be when

00:37:47.790 --> 00:37:51.570
you go to the social sector.

00:37:51.570 --> 00:37:55.800
If it's technical
capabilities, again, you'll

00:37:55.800 --> 00:37:57.769
learn faster here
than you will there.

00:37:57.769 --> 00:38:00.060
But then, at some point, you
can bring it to government

00:38:00.060 --> 00:38:01.590
or to a nonprofit.

00:38:01.590 --> 00:38:03.960
If it's leadership
experience, that's

00:38:03.960 --> 00:38:06.110
a different type of thing.

00:38:06.110 --> 00:38:07.990
Or if it's innovation
experience,

00:38:07.990 --> 00:38:09.573
those are the kinds
of things that you

00:38:09.573 --> 00:38:12.330
can develop great expertise
in at a place like Google

00:38:12.330 --> 00:38:14.760
and then, eventually, be
able to cross-fertilize that

00:38:14.760 --> 00:38:17.320
to other types of organizations.

00:38:17.320 --> 00:38:19.945
JACQUELLINE FULLER: I think the
other thing that I tell folks--

00:38:19.945 --> 00:38:22.641
because I get asked this
question a lot as well-- is,

00:38:22.641 --> 00:38:24.390
especially if you're
right out of college,

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:27.000
I strongly encourage people to
go get their transferable skill

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:30.820
in business, whether that's
accounting, or marketing,

00:38:30.820 --> 00:38:31.970
or coding--

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:34.660
get-- really do what
Ann Mei was saying,

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:37.630
but be careful that
you don't create

00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:40.742
a lifestyle that's
unsustainable to work

00:38:40.742 --> 00:38:41.950
in government or non-profits.

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:43.720
Because those same
people who I counsel,

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:46.140
sometimes I check
in five years later,

00:38:46.140 --> 00:38:48.190
and they're like, ah,
man, I got this mortgage.

00:38:48.190 --> 00:38:50.670
And yeah, I wanted to do--

00:38:50.670 --> 00:38:53.220
go work for Give
directly, but I can't.

00:38:53.220 --> 00:38:57.640
So there's some
practicalities to it, too,

00:38:57.640 --> 00:39:02.710
in terms of freeing yourself
to do the kinds of things

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:05.110
that you want to do
at a certain season.

00:39:05.110 --> 00:39:06.970
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah,
that's a great point.

00:39:06.970 --> 00:39:11.050
And the other way to do it is
not necessarily to have it be

00:39:11.050 --> 00:39:14.740
a one-way shift, that I
think this fellowship that

00:39:14.740 --> 00:39:16.480
you've talked about,
which sounds new--

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:17.350
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
Which he did.

00:39:17.350 --> 00:39:18.510
ANN MEI CHANG:
Oh, which you did.

00:39:18.510 --> 00:39:20.890
Is something that didn't
exist when I was at Google,

00:39:20.890 --> 00:39:22.990
I made up my own
fellowship, essentially--

00:39:22.990 --> 00:39:25.540
took a leave of absence.

00:39:25.540 --> 00:39:27.970
But the US government now
has a US digital services

00:39:27.970 --> 00:39:29.500
and 18F where
they're taking people

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:31.360
in for like one or two years.

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:33.410
And then, you can
go back to your job.

00:39:33.410 --> 00:39:36.052
And so for some people,
it doesn't necessarily

00:39:36.052 --> 00:39:37.760
make sense for it to
be a one-way street.

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:39.176
You may want to
come back, but you

00:39:39.176 --> 00:39:41.470
could take a year or
two out and do something

00:39:41.470 --> 00:39:43.289
to contribute back.

00:39:43.289 --> 00:39:44.830
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
Any idea on where

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:47.590
to fundraise when nonprofit
needs to be agile--

00:39:47.590 --> 00:39:49.090
try, fail, iterate--
without showing

00:39:49.090 --> 00:39:51.340
appealing concrete
impact numbers to donor?

00:39:51.340 --> 00:39:53.560
ANN MEI CHANG:
Yes, that is hard.

00:39:53.560 --> 00:39:57.580
Because most big
donors tend to like

00:39:57.580 --> 00:40:04.390
to fund very
rigid-defined programs.

00:40:04.390 --> 00:40:05.620
The good news is that--

00:40:05.620 --> 00:40:07.090
JACQUELLINE FULLER: And they
like the big reach numbers.

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:08.260
ANN MEI CHANG: Yes, they do.

00:40:08.260 --> 00:40:10.009
JACQUELLINE FULLER:
Speaking for a friend.

00:40:13.276 --> 00:40:16.902
ANN MEI CHANG: So it's hard to
answer this in a general sense.

00:40:16.902 --> 00:40:19.360
The good news is I think more
and more donors are waking up

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:19.859
to this.

00:40:19.859 --> 00:40:22.300
I spend a lot of time going
around talking to donors.

00:40:22.300 --> 00:40:25.270
And both-- there is a lot
of more innovative, smaller

00:40:25.270 --> 00:40:31.670
donors, like Google.org, Echoing
Green, Draper Richards Kaplan,

00:40:31.670 --> 00:40:32.890
JACQUELLINE FULLER: GiveWell.

00:40:32.890 --> 00:40:33.889
ANN MEI CHANG: GiveWell.

00:40:33.889 --> 00:40:37.330
So there's a lot of these
smaller, more innovative

00:40:37.330 --> 00:40:41.950
donors, if you will,
that specialize in--

00:40:41.950 --> 00:40:46.180
Mulago Foundation here-- that
specialize in kind of helping--

00:40:46.180 --> 00:40:48.970
allowing people to iterate
and failed an experiment

00:40:48.970 --> 00:40:49.540
and so forth.

00:40:49.540 --> 00:40:52.990
And so finding the relevant
ones in your space is great.

00:40:52.990 --> 00:40:55.480
The other good news is that
more and more of l big donors

00:40:55.480 --> 00:40:58.060
are also starting to do
this-- so not necessarily

00:40:58.060 --> 00:40:59.500
in the core of
what they're doing,

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:01.695
but almost every donor
now has something

00:41:01.695 --> 00:41:03.820
on this side where they
have more flexible funding.

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:06.970
So at USAID, we had the
development innovation ventures

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:08.980
that was modeled after
venture capital that

00:41:08.980 --> 00:41:12.520
did tiered funding that started
at $100,000, and $1 million,

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:15.369
and $5 million, where we
could take a lot more risk.

00:41:15.369 --> 00:41:17.410
And then, we spun out the
Global Innovation Fund.

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:18.035
That's similar.

00:41:18.035 --> 00:41:19.420
We have the grand
challenges that

00:41:19.420 --> 00:41:25.070
are similar on specific issues,
where we need better solutions.

00:41:25.070 --> 00:41:27.280
So there's a lot of
different things out there.

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:30.070
Whoever asked this question,
I'm happy to talk to, depending

00:41:30.070 --> 00:41:30.940
on your specific type of thing.

00:41:30.940 --> 00:41:32.140
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Irwin's
done a lot of work--

00:41:32.140 --> 00:41:33.580
who asked the question--
has done a lot of work

00:41:33.580 --> 00:41:35.900
internally on Google's
social impact projects.

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:39.340
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah, and I
would encourage you all that,

00:41:39.340 --> 00:41:42.460
as you donate money,
also, as donors yourself,

00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:45.130
even if you're not a huge
mega donor like the Gates

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:47.620
Foundation, you can
help organizations

00:41:47.620 --> 00:41:49.840
by giving them
unrestricted money,

00:41:49.840 --> 00:41:52.750
to allow them to do this
kind of experimentation.

00:41:52.750 --> 00:41:55.300
JACQUELLINE FULLER: If you
don't have the time or knowhow

00:41:55.300 --> 00:41:57.490
to do the research
to find those,

00:41:57.490 --> 00:41:59.650
you can use proxies
like GiveWell

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:01.840
and are groups like
Fast Forward, who

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:05.150
are funding tech-based
non-profits, who

00:42:05.150 --> 00:42:10.220
you can use them as a proxy
for really understanding deeply

00:42:10.220 --> 00:42:10.945
the impact.

00:42:13.741 --> 00:42:16.240
AUDIENCE: I was hoping you could
talk a little bit about how

00:42:16.240 --> 00:42:19.060
you would make the pitch
for this type of approach

00:42:19.060 --> 00:42:20.936
in industries where--

00:42:20.936 --> 00:42:22.810
like the government for
example, where things

00:42:22.810 --> 00:42:23.890
tend to move a lot slower.

00:42:23.890 --> 00:42:24.790
Because I can
imagine if you were

00:42:24.790 --> 00:42:27.010
to take this approach--
like, you give a couple

00:42:27.010 --> 00:42:29.349
examples of how spots in
the federal government

00:42:29.349 --> 00:42:31.390
are becoming more innovative
with their spending,

00:42:31.390 --> 00:42:34.150
but they tend to be very niche
programs, whereas I can imagine

00:42:34.150 --> 00:42:36.499
if you took this to a
career program officer,

00:42:36.499 --> 00:42:38.290
they might perceive of
someone from Silicon

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:40.030
Valley as an outsider.

00:42:40.030 --> 00:42:42.096
So how do you make a
pitch for rapid iteration

00:42:42.096 --> 00:42:44.470
in a place where the culture
is kind of like, well, we've

00:42:44.470 --> 00:42:45.755
always done it this way.

00:42:45.755 --> 00:42:47.546
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah,
it's a great question.

00:42:47.546 --> 00:42:50.080
I mean, government is
a huge institution,

00:42:50.080 --> 00:42:51.970
and it changes very slowly.

00:42:51.970 --> 00:42:55.060
The good news is that
there are career people.

00:42:55.060 --> 00:42:58.120
So this was, essentially,
my charter at USAID.

00:42:58.120 --> 00:42:59.860
I was the first
executive director

00:42:59.860 --> 00:43:01.480
for the Global Development Lab.

00:43:01.480 --> 00:43:04.540
We were set up as a bureau
to really promote-- you know,

00:43:04.540 --> 00:43:06.040
transform global development.

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:08.830
And we're a little
corner of the agency,

00:43:08.830 --> 00:43:10.900
but our mission
was to go reach out

00:43:10.900 --> 00:43:13.420
to other parts of the
agency, find those advocates,

00:43:13.420 --> 00:43:15.610
work with them to
build success stories.

00:43:15.610 --> 00:43:19.090
So it's just like
adoption of any new thing.

00:43:19.090 --> 00:43:20.620
You have to go step by step.

00:43:20.620 --> 00:43:23.310
And so we would start by
experimenting ourselves,

00:43:23.310 --> 00:43:25.690
showing it could be done,
then we would partner

00:43:25.690 --> 00:43:27.640
with the early adopters
across the agency

00:43:27.640 --> 00:43:30.250
that we could find, the Senior
Foreign Service officers, who

00:43:30.250 --> 00:43:33.220
were like mission directors,
but who are forward leaning,

00:43:33.220 --> 00:43:35.680
and we'd get a handful of
them to try stuff with us

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:38.590
and show that they could do it,
and they had their own network

00:43:38.590 --> 00:43:41.560
of other Senior Foreign Service
officers that trusted them,

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:44.590
that they could then tell
and then be our advocates,

00:43:44.590 --> 00:43:46.190
and spread the word further.

00:43:46.190 --> 00:43:49.060
And so it's step by step,
that kind of adoption

00:43:49.060 --> 00:43:50.581
curve that takes a long time.

00:43:50.581 --> 00:43:52.330
And one of the most
exciting things for me

00:43:52.330 --> 00:43:54.360
in writing this book is--

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:56.830
I left USAID and government
