00:46:58.377 --> 00:47:00.710
I'm not sure the kind of
projects you're thinking about.

00:47:00.710 --> 00:47:02.780
There's such a range of
public private partnerships.

00:47:02.780 --> 00:47:03.988
That's why I was asking that.

00:47:03.988 --> 00:47:05.090
We worked on at USAID--

00:47:05.090 --> 00:47:07.980
I was responsible for our
partnerships office as well.

00:47:07.980 --> 00:47:11.960
And so one of the
categories is what

00:47:11.960 --> 00:47:13.370
people call "shared value."

00:47:13.370 --> 00:47:16.310
So a classic is
Starbucks working

00:47:16.310 --> 00:47:20.570
or Walmart working to source
from smallholder farmers

00:47:20.570 --> 00:47:22.610
or from disadvantaged
populations

00:47:22.610 --> 00:47:25.296
to try to create economic
growth for those folks

00:47:25.296 --> 00:47:27.920
but while getting the goods that
they need for their own supply

00:47:27.920 --> 00:47:28.650
chains.

00:47:28.650 --> 00:47:32.390
So that's something where we
will cross-subsidize, where

00:47:32.390 --> 00:47:35.840
grant money can go to do
that technical assistance,

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:38.537
to go find all the farmers,
build collectives, and so

00:47:38.537 --> 00:47:40.370
forth, and connect them
to the supply chains

00:47:40.370 --> 00:47:42.078
that then companies
can kind of take over

00:47:42.078 --> 00:47:45.180
and be able to operate
on an ongoing basis.

00:47:45.180 --> 00:47:46.700
We also did things--

00:47:46.700 --> 00:47:50.460
at the lab, for example, we
would fund for-profit entities

00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:52.910
as well as nonprofit
entities in the early stages

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:56.760
to de-risk their new innovation.

00:47:56.760 --> 00:48:01.785
So we did a lot with the
off-grid energy sector, where

00:48:01.785 --> 00:48:03.740
the sort of pay-as-you
solar, where

00:48:03.740 --> 00:48:05.300
we put in some of
the earliest money

00:48:05.300 --> 00:48:08.540
to experiment with these
pay-as-you go solar systems,

00:48:08.540 --> 00:48:12.140
and then over time, as
the systems were proven,

00:48:12.140 --> 00:48:14.720
as they became financially self
sustainable, impact investors

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:16.600
started coming in to
be able to fund them

00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:18.910
and at a much, much
greater degree than we

00:48:18.910 --> 00:48:20.180
would have been able to.

00:48:20.180 --> 00:48:22.607
And so there's lots
of different ways.

00:48:22.607 --> 00:48:25.190
And I think a lot of these kind
of public private partnerships

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:28.937
like the EYElliance I
talked about earlier, where

00:48:28.937 --> 00:48:30.770
private sector and
governments come together

00:48:30.770 --> 00:48:31.610
for collective action.

00:48:31.610 --> 00:48:33.530
I started something that Google
was involved with called,

00:48:33.530 --> 00:48:35.300
The Alliance for
Affordable Internet that

00:48:35.300 --> 00:48:38.840
was looking at how do we expand
access to internet around

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:42.890
the world by addressing market
failures and policy failures.

00:48:42.890 --> 00:48:46.249
So just a few examples,
but very important.

00:48:46.249 --> 00:48:48.290
JACQUELLINE FULLER: So we
have four minutes left,

00:48:48.290 --> 00:48:51.470
so I wonder if we could
try to hit our remaining

00:48:51.470 --> 00:48:53.192
questions quickly.

00:48:53.192 --> 00:48:55.400
ANN MEI CHANG: So one
[INAUDIBLE] implied schools are

00:48:55.400 --> 00:48:57.590
so static is that it's hard
to test iterate on other

00:48:57.590 --> 00:48:58.580
people's children's.

00:48:58.580 --> 00:49:00.537
What are ways innovative,
and even radical,

00:49:00.537 --> 00:49:02.120
ideas can be validated
without risking

00:49:02.120 --> 00:49:04.310
the well-being of other folks?

00:49:04.310 --> 00:49:05.310
That's a great question.

00:49:05.310 --> 00:49:07.940
So I think a couple
answers to that.

00:49:07.940 --> 00:49:10.250
One is on the Summit
Public Schools thing.

00:49:10.250 --> 00:49:11.630
This was like an opt-in.

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:13.335
People knew that their
kids were going--

00:49:13.335 --> 00:49:15.710
it wasn't like we were going
to experiment their children

00:49:15.710 --> 00:49:16.880
and not tell you.

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:19.304
It's that they saw enough
value was being provided there,

00:49:19.304 --> 00:49:20.720
and they felt like
they were still

00:49:20.720 --> 00:49:23.095
going to get a better education
than they would otherwise

00:49:23.095 --> 00:49:24.262
that people opted into this.

00:49:24.262 --> 00:49:26.178
And I think that's
important, that people need

00:49:26.178 --> 00:49:27.446
to make have informed consent.

00:49:27.446 --> 00:49:28.820
And that can be
a little trickier

00:49:28.820 --> 00:49:31.610
when you're working with
vulnerable populations.

00:49:31.610 --> 00:49:33.200
Two things I would say to this.

00:49:33.200 --> 00:49:35.870
One is that-- it's
one of the reasons

00:49:35.870 --> 00:49:37.110
that we need to start small.

00:49:37.110 --> 00:49:40.220
So when you experiment with only
a very small number of people,

00:49:40.220 --> 00:49:42.740
you can pay much more
attention to making sure

00:49:42.740 --> 00:49:45.400
that they are made whole and
that nothing bad happens,

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:47.090
there's not unintended
consequences.

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:49.250
Because you can watch what
happens with five people

00:49:49.250 --> 00:49:51.390
much more easily than
thousands of people.

00:49:51.390 --> 00:49:54.540
The other is, I think that-- so
we need to tier up those risks,

00:49:54.540 --> 00:49:56.780
not take too big a risk
before we're ready.

00:49:56.780 --> 00:49:59.240
The other is, I
think we also need

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:02.600
to ask the question of, what is
the risk of not doing anything?

00:50:02.600 --> 00:50:04.710
So you think of
vaccines, for example.

00:50:04.710 --> 00:50:06.830
If no one was ever given
the first polio vaccine--

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:08.570
there was a risk to
that person's life

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:09.980
who got the first polio vaccine.

00:50:09.980 --> 00:50:12.380
There millions of people
would have died otherwise.

00:50:12.380 --> 00:50:14.172
But you don't
irresponsibly just randomly

00:50:14.172 --> 00:50:15.380
give someone a polio vaccine.

00:50:15.380 --> 00:50:17.466
You test in a Petri dish,
then you test it with rats,

00:50:17.466 --> 00:50:18.632
then you test it in monkeys.

00:50:18.632 --> 00:50:20.720
And then, when you get to
testing it with people,

00:50:20.720 --> 00:50:23.532
you watch very closely, but
you still take some risks.

00:50:23.532 --> 00:50:24.740
But it's that measured risks.

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:27.290
And you look at the upside
of, if you're successful,

00:50:27.290 --> 00:50:29.387
the number of people's
lives you can save.

00:50:29.387 --> 00:50:30.678
JACQUELLINE FULLER: [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:30.678 --> 00:50:32.231
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:50:32.231 --> 00:50:34.730
One of the sections in your
book that really stuck out to me

00:50:34.730 --> 00:50:37.130
was when you talk about the
different type of impact

00:50:37.130 --> 00:50:40.520
numbers that result from
both an e-commerce business.

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:42.910
You talk more about
the 30-day active.

00:50:42.910 --> 00:50:46.530
You could do sign-up
completes, et cetera,

00:50:46.530 --> 00:50:50.120
more Silicon Valley numbers
that we're used to, but then how

00:50:50.120 --> 00:50:54.170
the impact numbers for social
impact takes years to see that

00:50:54.170 --> 00:50:58.310
same type of result. So I
was wondering if you had any

00:50:58.310 --> 00:51:00.410
recommendations of
a set of numbers,

00:51:00.410 --> 00:51:02.030
maybe three
categories of numbers,

00:51:02.030 --> 00:51:03.840
that can sit in the middle--

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:06.890
so not quite 30-day
user active, but not

00:51:06.890 --> 00:51:09.680
quite like a
four-year RCT that can

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:12.710
help both funders
and nonprofits guide

00:51:12.710 --> 00:51:16.420
and tell the story of whether
or not a program is successful.

00:51:16.420 --> 00:51:20.052
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah, I can't
give you generic metrics

00:51:20.052 --> 00:51:22.010
because they're going to
be different depending

00:51:22.010 --> 00:51:24.740
on the type of intervention.

00:51:24.740 --> 00:51:27.350
What I would say is
that, I look at--

00:51:27.350 --> 00:51:30.200
almost every nonprofit
has a theory of change

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:32.822
for what-- you know, we're
going to train these farmers,

00:51:32.822 --> 00:51:35.030
then they're going to have
better farming techniques,

00:51:35.030 --> 00:51:37.140
then they're going to have
better yields for their crops,

00:51:37.140 --> 00:51:39.431
then you're going to have
higher incomes, and whatever.

00:51:39.431 --> 00:51:40.790
You have a theory of change.

00:51:40.790 --> 00:51:43.789
And part of testing for impact
is testing those linkages

00:51:43.789 --> 00:51:44.830
and the theory of change.

00:51:44.830 --> 00:51:46.700
We tend to create these
elaborate theories of change,

00:51:46.700 --> 00:51:48.320
and then put them
on the bookshelf,

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:49.850
and then just run through
the whole program,

00:51:49.850 --> 00:51:51.316
then try and do
an RCT at the end.

00:51:51.316 --> 00:51:52.940
But if you test each
of those linkages,

00:51:52.940 --> 00:51:54.590
it's like, if you
train the farmers,

00:51:54.590 --> 00:51:57.802
did they actually do what
you trained them to do?

00:51:57.802 --> 00:52:00.260
If they didn't, you don't have
to wait four years to figure

00:52:00.260 --> 00:52:01.510
out if their incomes increase.

00:52:01.510 --> 00:52:03.680
So what are those simpler
earlier indicators

00:52:03.680 --> 00:52:04.310
that tell you?

00:52:04.310 --> 00:52:06.410
And so summit public
schools did this

00:52:06.410 --> 00:52:09.599
by measuring learning
assessments each week to say,

00:52:09.599 --> 00:52:10.640
hey, we tried this thing.

00:52:10.640 --> 00:52:13.950
Did the students learn better
than doing it some other way?

00:52:13.950 --> 00:52:16.535
And so it really depends on the
nature of their intervention.

00:52:16.535 --> 00:52:18.410
JACQUELLINE FULLER: All
right, last question.

00:52:21.157 --> 00:52:24.620
AUDIENCE: So my sense is that
a lot of small organizations,

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:29.960
in particular, their thought
process is kind of, well, sure,

00:52:29.960 --> 00:52:32.720
it would be great to quantify
things and know how we're

00:52:32.720 --> 00:52:35.670
doing, but we're just spending
all of our energy and effort

00:52:35.670 --> 00:52:38.010
doing the real work
of the organization,

00:52:38.010 --> 00:52:40.980
helping the target
population, whatever it is.

00:52:40.980 --> 00:52:42.770
So how do you pitch
to those groups

00:52:42.770 --> 00:52:45.350
that reorienting
some of their efforts

00:52:45.350 --> 00:52:49.880
toward coming up with metrics,
quantifying things, tracking

00:52:49.880 --> 00:52:53.065
those metrics, is
worth the effort?

00:52:53.065 --> 00:52:55.820
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:52:55.820 --> 00:52:57.500
One is that, I think--

00:52:57.500 --> 00:52:58.810
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Change
funder behavior, number one.

00:52:58.810 --> 00:52:59.850
ANN MEI CHANG: Hold
them accountable.

00:52:59.850 --> 00:53:02.308
Because when your funders are
telling you, give us numbers,

00:53:02.308 --> 00:53:04.200
it's really hard to do
something different.

00:53:04.200 --> 00:53:06.870
JACQUELLINE FULLER: Give us
real numbers, give us outcomes.

00:53:06.870 --> 00:53:10.650
ANN MEI CHANG: Yeah, and also,
I think that in the book,

00:53:10.650 --> 00:53:14.000
I talk about starting
with an audacious goal.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.380
So too often-- it's a short
term, long-term tradeoff,

00:53:16.380 --> 00:53:16.880
right?

00:53:16.880 --> 00:53:18.500
You can deliver more
in the short term

00:53:18.500 --> 00:53:20.570
by just cranking out
stuff, but you're never

00:53:20.570 --> 00:53:22.190
going to bend the
curve to accelerate

00:53:22.190 --> 00:53:23.398
your growth in the long term.

00:53:23.398 --> 00:53:27.710
So you end up like the clean
water sanitation graph.

00:53:27.710 --> 00:53:33.360
And so it means setting
that audacious goal.

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:35.760
Because most
nonprofits have goals

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:38.890
that they can meet just by
working a little bit harder.

00:53:38.890 --> 00:53:42.129
And so if you have a goal that's
like 10% better than last year,

00:53:42.129 --> 00:53:43.420
there's no reason to take risk.

00:53:43.420 --> 00:53:44.670
There's no reason to innovate.

00:53:44.670 --> 00:53:46.470
There's no reason
to potentially fail.

00:53:46.470 --> 00:53:48.761
But if you have a goal that's
longer term, that's like,

00:53:48.761 --> 00:53:52.200
we've got to get to
10X, or 100X, or 1,000X,

00:53:52.200 --> 00:53:55.440
then as you're doing your
thing, you can sort of see,

00:53:55.440 --> 00:53:58.740
are you on your
trajectory to get there?

00:53:58.740 --> 00:54:01.930
And so I ask nonprofits, what's
your definition of success?

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:04.170
What does success look like
in 10 years or 20 years?

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:06.060
Push it out far enough
that they're not

00:54:06.060 --> 00:54:08.310
trying to project what they're
doing today, but then look at,

00:54:08.310 --> 00:54:09.820
are we on a trajectory
to get there?

00:54:09.820 --> 00:54:12.180
And if not, and this
is your mission, what

00:54:12.180 --> 00:54:16.230
do we need to do to try to shift
the curve so that we change

00:54:16.230 --> 00:54:17.280
the trajectory?

